1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:10,480
 >> Good morning ladies, good morning brothers and sisters.

2
00:00:10,480 --> 00:00:13,860
 >> [FOREIGN]

3
00:00:13,860 --> 00:00:18,000
 >> I wonder if everybody likes to eat these kind of foods.

4
00:00:18,000 --> 00:00:22,120
 >> [FOREIGN]

5
00:00:22,120 --> 00:00:25,640
 >> Steaks, lamb belly, these foods are rich in oil.

6
00:00:25,640 --> 00:00:32,760
 >> [FOREIGN]

7
00:00:32,760 --> 00:00:36,920
 >> The fat after being cooked at a high temperature melts in your mouth and

8
00:00:36,920 --> 00:00:38,200
 spreads out.

9
00:00:38,200 --> 00:00:46,040
 >> [FOREIGN]

10
00:00:46,040 --> 00:00:49,920
 >> If you only eat steak, lamb chops, or lamb belly for meal,

11
00:00:49,920 --> 00:00:53,380
 we would think all find this very greasy.

12
00:00:53,380 --> 00:00:57,040
 >> [FOREIGN]

13
00:00:57,040 --> 00:01:00,880
 >> I heard that Joe Osco was having a big sale this week.

14
00:01:00,880 --> 00:01:09,160
 >> [FOREIGN]

15
00:01:09,160 --> 00:01:12,840
 >> And their Angus beef this week was in a really good deal.

16
00:01:12,840 --> 00:01:15,520
 I was thinking to drive in there immediately and

17
00:01:15,520 --> 00:01:19,240
 to buy several more box while it was cheap.

18
00:01:19,240 --> 00:01:29,240
 >> [FOREIGN]

19
00:01:29,240 --> 00:01:34,820
 >> To my surprise, when I arrived, only empty shelves as you can see in the picture.

20
00:01:34,820 --> 00:01:40,020
 So I end up just grabbing three inexpensive thinly sliced steaks.

21
00:01:40,020 --> 00:01:44,100
 >> [FOREIGN]

22
00:01:44,100 --> 00:01:46,300
 >> In any case, it's very convenient for

23
00:01:46,300 --> 00:01:48,740
 modern people to eat beef or lamb.

24
00:01:48,740 --> 00:01:56,000
 >> [FOREIGN]

25
00:01:56,000 --> 00:02:00,260
 >> However, in ancient times, when the Jews still had temple,

26
00:02:00,260 --> 00:02:03,660
 it wasn't so easy for them to eat steak and lamb chops.

27
00:02:03,660 --> 00:02:12,580
 >> [FOREIGN]

28
00:02:12,580 --> 00:02:16,300
 >> They need to go to the temple to offer sacrifices.

29
00:02:16,300 --> 00:02:20,380
 Leaving some for the priest, some for God, and the rest for themselves.

30
00:02:20,380 --> 00:02:28,380
 >> [FOREIGN]

31
00:02:28,380 --> 00:02:31,740
 >> However, in the temple scene of Gospel of John,

32
00:02:31,740 --> 00:02:37,220
 Jesus actually drove out these cattle and sheep that represented sacrifice.

33
00:02:37,220 --> 00:02:44,200
 >> [FOREIGN]

34
00:02:44,200 --> 00:02:48,760
 >> What message does this story of cleansing the temple in the Gospel of John

35
00:02:48,760 --> 00:02:50,060
 convey to us?

36
00:02:50,060 --> 00:02:55,660
 >> [FOREIGN]

37
00:02:55,660 --> 00:02:57,220
 >> Before reading the scripture,

38
00:02:57,220 --> 00:02:59,660
 let's review the previous section today.

39
00:02:59,660 --> 00:03:06,580
 >> [FOREIGN]

40
00:03:06,580 --> 00:03:10,740
 >> Last time we mentioned that Jesus was asked to perform a miracle.

41
00:03:10,740 --> 00:03:14,860
 At the wedding in Cana, he performed an unexpected miracle.

42
00:03:14,860 --> 00:03:24,860
 >> [FOREIGN]

43
00:03:24,860 --> 00:03:29,020
 >> He transformed the unclean water originally intended for

44
00:03:29,020 --> 00:03:34,260
 purification rations and stored in stone jars into fine wine.

45
00:03:34,260 --> 00:03:38,140
 Thus, revealing God's glory and calling people back to God.

46
00:03:38,140 --> 00:03:46,620
 >> [FOREIGN]

47
00:03:46,620 --> 00:03:48,620
 >> The following passage continues this theme.

48
00:03:48,620 --> 00:03:50,860
 Let's read John 2, 12 to 25.

49
00:03:50,860 --> 00:04:00,260
 >> [FOREIGN]

50
00:04:00,260 --> 00:04:04,700
 >> After this refers to the events following Jesus' transforming

51
00:04:04,700 --> 00:04:07,380
 of water into wine at the wedding in Cana.

52
00:04:08,180 --> 00:04:15,420
 >> [FOREIGN]

53
00:04:15,420 --> 00:04:19,460
 >> Jesus went down to Capernaum with his mother, brothers,

54
00:04:19,460 --> 00:04:22,780
 and disciples and stayed there for a few days.

55
00:04:22,780 --> 00:04:29,860
 >> [FOREIGN]

56
00:04:29,860 --> 00:04:32,940
 >> When it was almost time for a Jewish Passover,

57
00:04:32,940 --> 00:04:35,900
 it's a very important holiday.

58
00:04:35,900 --> 00:04:38,140
 Jesus went up to Jerusalem.

59
00:04:38,140 --> 00:04:46,300
 >> [FOREIGN]

60
00:04:46,300 --> 00:04:50,300
 >> In the temple courts, he found people selling cattle, sheep, and

61
00:04:50,300 --> 00:04:54,140
 dogs, and others sitting at the tables, exchanging money.

62
00:04:54,140 --> 00:04:59,060
 >> [FOREIGN]

63
00:04:59,060 --> 00:05:02,060
 >> So Jesus made the whips out of the courts and

64
00:05:02,060 --> 00:05:05,260
 drove out all the sheep and cattle from the temple.

65
00:05:05,260 --> 00:05:15,260
 >> [FOREIGN]

66
00:05:15,260 --> 00:05:18,540
 >> Please note that cattle and sheep are not mentioned in

67
00:05:18,540 --> 00:05:22,740
 a synoptic Gospel account of cleansing the temple.

68
00:05:22,740 --> 00:05:26,860
 This is the unique account found only in Gospel of John.

69
00:05:26,860 --> 00:05:33,900
 >> [FOREIGN]

70
00:05:33,900 --> 00:05:36,820
 >> They poured out the money of those exchanging silver and

71
00:05:36,820 --> 00:05:38,340
 overturned their tables.

72
00:05:38,340 --> 00:05:48,340
 >> [FOREIGN]

73
00:05:48,340 --> 00:05:53,900
 >> To those who sold those, he said, get this out of here.

74
00:05:53,900 --> 00:05:56,780
 Stop turning my father's house into a market.

75
00:05:56,780 --> 00:06:06,780
 >> [FOREIGN]

76
00:06:06,780 --> 00:06:15,860
 >> Was Jesus opposing monetary transaction within the temple?

77
00:06:15,860 --> 00:06:20,100
 The phrase, the father's temple, is unique in the Gospel of John.

78
00:06:20,100 --> 00:06:24,140
 It is only instance in the entire Bible where father and

79
00:06:24,140 --> 00:06:25,740
 temple are used together.

80
00:06:27,580 --> 00:06:34,860
 >> [FOREIGN]

81
00:06:34,860 --> 00:06:38,820
 >> His disciples remember that it is written, zeal for

82
00:06:38,820 --> 00:06:41,020
 your house will consume me.

83
00:06:41,020 --> 00:06:46,820
 >> [FOREIGN]

84
00:06:46,820 --> 00:06:49,020
 >> The Jews then responded to him,

85
00:06:49,020 --> 00:06:53,260
 what sign can you show us to prove your authority to do all this?

86
00:06:53,260 --> 00:06:59,380
 >> [FOREIGN]

87
00:06:59,380 --> 00:07:00,500
 >> Jesus answered them,

88
00:07:00,500 --> 00:07:04,620
 destroy this temple and I will raise it again in three days.

89
00:07:04,620 --> 00:07:10,660
 >> [FOREIGN]

90
00:07:10,660 --> 00:07:14,540
 >> They replied, it has taken 46 years to build this temple and

91
00:07:14,540 --> 00:07:17,460
 you are going to raise it in three days?

92
00:07:17,460 --> 00:07:20,620
 >> [FOREIGN]

93
00:07:20,620 --> 00:07:24,140
 >> But the temple he had spoken of was his body.

94
00:07:24,140 --> 00:07:32,980
 >> [FOREIGN]

95
00:07:32,980 --> 00:07:34,700
 >> After he was raised from the dead,

96
00:07:34,700 --> 00:07:37,420
 his disciples recalled what he had said.

97
00:07:37,420 --> 00:07:40,860
 Then they believed the scripture and the words that Jesus had spoken.

98
00:07:40,860 --> 00:07:50,460
 >> [FOREIGN]

99
00:07:50,460 --> 00:07:54,340
 >> Now while he was in Jerusalem at the Passover Festival,

100
00:07:54,340 --> 00:07:56,740
 Passover is mentioned again here.

101
00:07:56,740 --> 00:07:59,740
 Clearly, Jesus wanted to remind him of something.

102
00:07:59,740 --> 00:08:04,740
 >> [FOREIGN]

103
00:08:04,740 --> 00:08:08,180
 >> Many people saw the signs he was performing and

104
00:08:08,180 --> 00:08:09,620
 believed in his name.

105
00:08:09,620 --> 00:08:14,620
 >> [FOREIGN]

106
00:08:14,620 --> 00:08:18,220
 >> But Jesus would not entrust himself to them for

107
00:08:18,220 --> 00:08:20,500
 he knew all people.

108
00:08:20,500 --> 00:08:28,020
 >> [FOREIGN]

109
00:08:28,020 --> 00:08:31,700
 >> He did not need any testimony about mankind for

110
00:08:31,700 --> 00:08:34,180
 he knew what was in each person.

111
00:08:34,180 --> 00:08:41,700
 >> [FOREIGN]

112
00:08:41,700 --> 00:08:46,260
 >> What exactly did Jesus know about people's heart that led him to perform

113
00:08:46,260 --> 00:08:48,820
 such a special cleansing of the temple?

114
00:08:48,820 --> 00:08:55,340
 >> [FOREIGN]

115
00:08:55,340 --> 00:08:59,140
 >> After reading the scripture, we will find at least three main problems.

116
00:08:59,140 --> 00:09:09,140
 >> [FOREIGN]

117
00:09:10,340 --> 00:09:16,700
 >> The story of Jesus driving away the cattle and sheep is unique to the Gospel of John.

118
00:09:16,700 --> 00:09:20,020
 The cattle and sheep are the core of sacrifice.

119
00:09:20,020 --> 00:09:22,340
 What does it mean that Jesus drove them away?

120
00:09:22,340 --> 00:09:31,340
 >> [FOREIGN]

121
00:09:31,340 --> 00:09:34,180
 >> The passage mentioned Passover twice.

122
00:09:34,180 --> 00:09:37,940
 What is the significance of cleansing the temple on Passover?

123
00:09:37,940 --> 00:09:42,820
 >> [FOREIGN]

124
00:09:42,820 --> 00:09:44,900
 >> After Jesus cleansed the temple,

125
00:09:44,900 --> 00:09:47,460
 did he know what was in people's hearts?

126
00:09:47,460 --> 00:09:56,140
 >> [FOREIGN]

127
00:09:56,140 --> 00:09:57,940
 >> After answering these three questions,

128
00:09:57,940 --> 00:10:00,940
 we will understand what Jesus wanted to tell us.

129
00:10:00,940 --> 00:10:07,820
 >> [FOREIGN]

130
00:10:07,820 --> 00:10:10,460
 >> What is also today's topic,

131
00:10:10,460 --> 00:10:13,780
 cleanse your heart of its cattle and sheep.

132
00:10:13,780 --> 00:10:18,060
 What exactly do this cattle and sheep symbolize in our lives?

133
00:10:18,060 --> 00:10:21,380
 >> [FOREIGN]

134
00:10:21,380 --> 00:10:23,620
 >> If you're ready, we can start.

135
00:10:23,620 --> 00:10:28,220
 >> [FOREIGN]

136
00:10:28,220 --> 00:10:31,020
 >> What did Jesus especially emphasize,

137
00:10:31,020 --> 00:10:34,500
 using a whip to drive away cattle and sheep?

138
00:10:34,500 --> 00:10:42,580
 >> [FOREIGN]

139
00:10:42,580 --> 00:10:46,820
 >> It was actually quite normal for the temple to have cattle and sheep.

140
00:10:46,820 --> 00:10:51,260
 During the second temple period, animal sacrifices were necessary.

141
00:10:51,260 --> 00:11:01,700
 >> [FOREIGN]

142
00:11:01,700 --> 00:11:05,420
 >> The burnt offering, an optimum offering,

143
00:11:05,420 --> 00:11:09,300
 the peace offerings recorded in the latificates,

144
00:11:09,300 --> 00:11:15,180
 are all associated with sacrificial animals such as cattle, sheep, and doves.

145
00:11:15,180 --> 00:11:22,460
 >> [FOREIGN]

146
00:11:22,460 --> 00:11:28,060
 >> During Passover, pilgrims from afar flocked to the temple,

147
00:11:28,060 --> 00:11:31,900
 unable to bring suitable sacrificial animals.

148
00:11:31,900 --> 00:11:43,900
 >> [FOREIGN]

149
00:11:43,900 --> 00:11:47,820
 >> Therefore, sacrificial markets were set up near the temple,

150
00:11:47,820 --> 00:11:52,620
 and even within its ground for the convenience of buying and using immediately.

151
00:11:52,620 --> 00:11:58,100
 This is reasonable and necessary from an institutional perspective.

152
00:11:58,100 --> 00:12:02,140
 >> [FOREIGN]

153
00:12:02,140 --> 00:12:08,180
 >> The sacrificial animals must be without defects and cannot be purchased casually.

154
00:12:08,180 --> 00:12:14,340
 >> [FOREIGN]

155
00:12:14,340 --> 00:12:19,420
 >> To make it convenient for people from other places and avoid the risk of injury

156
00:12:19,420 --> 00:12:24,860
 and uncleanliness to the sacrificial animals to long journeys.

157
00:12:24,860 --> 00:12:31,700
 >> [FOREIGN]

158
00:12:31,700 --> 00:12:34,540
 >> Temple taxes require a specific currency.

159
00:12:34,540 --> 00:12:37,260
 Exchange services must be provided.

160
00:12:37,260 --> 00:12:45,300
 >> [FOREIGN]

161
00:12:45,300 --> 00:12:50,220
 >> This is similar to how monetary transactions are heard in more modern temples,

162
00:12:50,220 --> 00:12:53,140
 such as adding oil to incense,

163
00:12:53,140 --> 00:12:54,820
 buying incense in candles,

164
00:12:54,820 --> 00:12:57,580
 and having fortune sticks interpreted.

165
00:12:57,580 --> 00:13:02,940
 >> [FOREIGN]

166
00:13:02,940 --> 00:13:07,100
 >> Since buying and selling cattle and sheep were originally normal,

167
00:13:07,100 --> 00:13:11,140
 why did Jesus break this norm?

168
00:13:11,140 --> 00:13:13,140
 >> [FOREIGN]

169
00:13:13,140 --> 00:13:16,540
 >> The key lies in the Father's temple.

170
00:13:16,540 --> 00:13:23,220
 >> [FOREIGN]

171
00:13:23,220 --> 00:13:25,340
 >> In the Synodic Gospels,

172
00:13:25,340 --> 00:13:29,220
 Jesus quotes, "My house will be a house of prayer,

173
00:13:29,220 --> 00:13:32,420
 but you have made it a den of thieves."

174
00:13:32,420 --> 00:13:43,540
 >> [FOREIGN]

175
00:13:43,540 --> 00:13:45,540
 >> However, in the Gospel of John,

176
00:13:45,540 --> 00:13:48,100
 it is the disciples who quote,

177
00:13:48,100 --> 00:13:51,700
 "My soul is burning with anxiety for your house,"

178
00:13:51,700 --> 00:13:55,420
 while Jesus refers to it as the Father's house.

179
00:13:55,420 --> 00:14:04,500
 >> [FOREIGN]

180
00:14:04,500 --> 00:14:09,500
 >> This shows that Jesus drove away the cattle and sheep to emphasize that it was

181
00:14:09,500 --> 00:14:14,180
 Jehovah's land and he did not want it to become a place of buying and selling.

182
00:14:14,180 --> 00:14:21,940
 >> [FOREIGN]

183
00:14:21,940 --> 00:14:25,620
 >> But Jesus wasn't simply against commercial activities.

184
00:14:25,620 --> 00:14:29,100
 He was against the motives behind buying and selling.

185
00:14:29,100 --> 00:14:37,660
 >> [FOREIGN]

186
00:14:37,660 --> 00:14:43,460
 >> In Jesus' time, temples often became places of corruptions and power struggles.

187
00:14:43,460 --> 00:14:51,820
 >> [FOREIGN]

188
00:14:51,820 --> 00:14:57,220
 >> For example, the Temple of Apollo in Greece was not only a financial center,

189
00:14:57,220 --> 00:15:03,980
 but its auricular service were also frequently exploited by politicians.

190
00:15:03,980 --> 00:15:14,180
 >> [FOREIGN]

191
00:15:14,180 --> 00:15:19,620
 >> Many Roman temples also become money-laundering centers for armies and

192
00:15:19,620 --> 00:15:26,420
 officials to store their spoils, engage in usury, and invade taxes.

193
00:15:26,420 --> 00:15:37,140
 >> [FOREIGN]

194
00:15:37,140 --> 00:15:42,740
 >> Officials even bought and sold priesthood and maintained their monopoly,

195
00:15:42,740 --> 00:15:47,540
 forming a system of using the name of God to amass wealth.

196
00:15:47,540 --> 00:16:06,060
 >> [FOREIGN]

197
00:16:06,060 --> 00:16:09,820
 >> This culture also permitted the Jewish temple.

198
00:16:09,820 --> 00:16:12,820
 Beginning with the Maccabean dynasty,

199
00:16:12,820 --> 00:16:19,820
 the trading system became the political tools, priestly positions were bought and

200
00:16:19,820 --> 00:16:23,820
 sold, and what should have belonged to God was embezzled.

201
00:16:23,820 --> 00:16:28,980
 >> [FOREIGN]

202
00:16:28,980 --> 00:16:35,180
 >> Therefore, the act of cleansing indicates the temple's defilement.

203
00:16:35,180 --> 00:16:44,060
 >> [FOREIGN]

204
00:16:44,060 --> 00:16:49,660
 >> Originally intended to facilitate people's worship to God,

205
00:16:49,660 --> 00:16:55,660
 the system, it has been corrupted by human greed and attachment to power.

206
00:16:55,660 --> 00:17:00,620
 >> [FOREIGN]

207
00:17:00,620 --> 00:17:05,140
 >> The problem lies not in the system itself, but in people's minds.

208
00:17:05,140 --> 00:17:09,740
 >> [FOREIGN]

209
00:17:09,740 --> 00:17:14,740
 >> Driving away the cattle and sheep is unique to the Gospel of John.

210
00:17:14,740 --> 00:17:26,100
 >> [FOREIGN]

211
00:17:26,100 --> 00:17:32,900
 >> In Leviticus, cattle and sheep are central to the peace offering,

212
00:17:32,900 --> 00:17:37,140
 where people offer their fat to God and share the remainder,

213
00:17:37,140 --> 00:17:40,540
 thus expressing their belonging to God.

214
00:17:40,540 --> 00:17:49,420
 >> [FOREIGN]

215
00:17:49,420 --> 00:17:55,260
 >> The reason for emphasizing Passover again is to remind us that some things

216
00:17:55,260 --> 00:18:00,340
 belong to God that humans cannot transgress them.

217
00:18:00,340 --> 00:18:10,100
 >> [FOREIGN]

218
00:18:10,100 --> 00:18:15,620
 >> The disciples quote Psalm 69, which describes David's desire to build a temple

219
00:18:15,620 --> 00:18:19,780
 for God, even in difficult circumstances, and his hope for

220
00:18:19,780 --> 00:18:23,060
 a return of people's hearts.

221
00:18:23,060 --> 00:18:33,060
 >> [FOREIGN]

222
00:18:33,060 --> 00:18:46,260
 >> Psalm 31 says, this will please the Lord more than an ox.

223
00:18:46,260 --> 00:18:49,980
 This suggests that when people's heart corrupt the system,

224
00:18:49,980 --> 00:18:57,060
 sacrifices lose their meaning, and even cattle and sheep become worthless.

225
00:18:57,060 --> 00:19:00,700
 >> [FOREIGN]

226
00:19:00,700 --> 00:19:03,700
 >> Chinese people value reciprocity.

227
00:19:03,700 --> 00:19:06,740
 >> [FOREIGN]

228
00:19:06,740 --> 00:19:10,260
 >> Giving gifts to express affection is a good thing.

229
00:19:10,260 --> 00:19:16,580
 >> [FOREIGN]

230
00:19:16,580 --> 00:19:23,380
 >> But if this transactional mentality is applied to one's relationship with God,

231
00:19:23,380 --> 00:19:26,220
 then the priorities are reversed.

232
00:19:26,220 --> 00:19:35,460
 >> [FOREIGN]

233
00:19:35,460 --> 00:19:37,900
 >> If God bless me, I will give more.

234
00:19:37,900 --> 00:19:41,060
 If God does not bless me, I will give less.

235
00:19:41,060 --> 00:19:43,180
 This has become a transaction.

236
00:19:43,180 --> 00:19:54,300
 >> [FOREIGN]

237
00:19:54,300 --> 00:20:00,980
 >> Just like how people are tired of giving mooncakes during mid-autumn festival,

238
00:20:00,980 --> 00:20:05,780
 because it has become a cold and impersonal routine.

239
00:20:05,780 --> 00:20:15,780
 >> [FOREIGN]

240
00:20:15,780 --> 00:20:22,740
 >> When we give money, time, spiritual support to the church,

241
00:20:22,740 --> 00:20:27,500
 are we making a transactional offering, or do we believe that everything comes

242
00:20:27,500 --> 00:20:32,020
 from God and we are simply fulfilling our duty to give back?

243
00:20:32,020 --> 00:20:36,820
 >> [FOREIGN]

244
00:20:36,820 --> 00:20:42,140
 >> Jesus reminds us that cattle and sheep symbolize our hearts turning to God.

245
00:20:42,140 --> 00:20:49,500
 >> [FOREIGN]

246
00:20:49,500 --> 00:20:54,340
 >> Our lives, assets, and talents are not entirely our own.

247
00:20:54,340 --> 00:21:04,340
 >> [FOREIGN]

248
00:21:04,340 --> 00:21:10,620
 >> Driving away the sheep and cattle in our hearts doesn't mean abstaining from meat

249
00:21:10,620 --> 00:21:19,140
 or offering sacrifices, but rather watching our own hearts and not transgressing in God's name.

250
00:21:19,140 --> 00:21:29,140
 >> [FOREIGN]

251
00:21:29,140 --> 00:21:40,140
 >> My wife and I discussed two methods of donation,

252
00:21:40,140 --> 00:21:43,900
 automatic transfer or manual transfer.

253
00:21:43,900 --> 00:21:46,660
 Which one is more heartfelt?

254
00:21:46,660 --> 00:21:49,740
 >> [FOREIGN]

255
00:21:49,740 --> 00:21:52,860
 >> In fact, both can become formalism.

256
00:21:52,860 --> 00:22:02,860
 >> [FOREIGN]

257
00:22:02,860 --> 00:22:09,900
 >> If giving is merely a matter of feeling heartache or

258
00:22:09,900 --> 00:22:14,260
 pain without recognizing it as God's grace,

259
00:22:14,260 --> 00:22:19,500
 then it's just an act, not a genuine affirmation that everything belongs to the God.

260
00:22:19,500 --> 00:22:29,500
 >> [FOREIGN]

261
00:22:29,500 --> 00:22:38,180
 >> The same applies to time.

262
